just some notes on being a tl to turn into a post later:

- Growth goals (aka advice on how to be a TL)
  - I think we knew I was going to talk about communication and organization
  - Organization: Lean on Kem for this sort of stuff, especially project planning - you're a great coder and you'll need to protect your time to make direct contributions. Set a goal of knowing what's going on so you can mentor people and watch out for bugs coming down the pike, but don't be the one reminding people to update their task status.
    - One more on this: write it down! so much of our job happens in spur-of-the-moment conversations; make sure that you take notes in meetings and share them, or put it in a slack comment (maybe not anymore with the retention policy) or just create an asana task. Make this ugly - don't worry about formatting or wording - but just make sure that you can link to it later when you get the same question again or need to remind yourself.
  - communication:
    - Being a TL is a data compression problem. You spend ~40% of your time learning about every little detail that's going on with partner teams, systems you're investigating, and projects your teammates are working on, and then when people ask you about it you have like 5 minutes to explain everything they need to know.
    - TL / senior roles in general move from a technical solution finding orientation to a business value orientation - think "how will what I do or say here help achieve the concrete goals of the business, not just be the locally-correct technical outcome?".
    - Putting these together, sometimes we have a tendency to get excited about technical problems and want to share all the insights and philosophy and ideas he has about them, and this is honestly great in situations like office hours. In meetings with leads or with other teams, the goal should instead be to understand what they want / need to know, and to communicate that clearly without distractions or fluff. This isn't just advice to "stop talking so much" - there's a difficult problem of judgement to understand what information is crucial, and that should be stated clearly or even repeated, but we want to make sure it sticks by not giving other distracting info.
    - This whole pattern will be even more amplified in communications for mass consumption, like when we want to get other teams to start using the RBAC platform. Think like a politician, come up with short "slogans" that convey the key principles (examples: "a role is just a bag of permissions", "the Permissions API is the single source of truth for permissions at asana"), and repeat them to build a consistent message.
      - Since this is 2026, maybe also think about how to get coding agents to understand these principles as well - e.g. how can we minimize the chance that a well meaning agent tries to re-implement a permission on the frontend? I expect you'd probably use the same communication cues that you would use for humans, like writing "**IMPORTANT DO NOT SKIP**:", just in their agent docs instead. But this will be an area to experiment and learn in as things change.